I'm not so sure about that.

526
00:19:23,685 --> 00:19:25,419
The ghost said that we couldn't save him.

527
00:19:25,487 --> 00:19:26,820
Maybe it wasn't a threat.

528
00:19:26,888 --> 00:19:28,822
Maybe he was worried about him.

529
00:19:47,705 --> 00:19:49,939
You're his father, aren't you?

530
00:19:50,007 --> 00:19:51,441
Yes.

531
00:19:51,508 --> 00:19:53,342
I wasn't there for him.

532
00:19:55,879 --> 00:19:57,779
He needs me now.

533
00:20:17,064 --> 00:20:18,131
You said the ghost was close to the guy?

534
00:20:18,298 --> 00:20:19,532
Their foreheads were touching.

535
00:20:19,599 --> 00:20:21,500
And jim said that the patient
had the same nightmare,

536
00:20:21,568 --> 00:20:23,468
Of someone slashing a woman with a knife.

537
00:20:23,536 --> 00:20:25,103
That sounds about right.

538
00:20:25,171 --> 00:20:26,405
It sounds about right for what?

539
00:20:26,472 --> 00:20:27,673
They call it threading.

540
00:20:27,740 --> 00:20:29,441
I found 3 different references
to it in the library.

541
00:20:29,508 --> 00:20:30,976
Why is it called threading?

542
00:20:31,043 --> 00:20:32,644
It's when a ghost weaves images or visions

543
00:20:32,712 --> 00:20:34,312
Into the mind of a civilian.

544
00:20:34,380 --> 00:20:35,680
A civilian?

545
00:20:35,748 --> 00:20:37,549
Someone who's not a sensitive,
like you or aiden.

546
00:20:37,616 --> 00:20:39,817
It's supposed to be easier
with physical proximity.

547
00:20:39,885 --> 00:20:41,452
How easy?

548
00:20:41,520 --> 00:20:43,454
Well, you don't have to suppress
a person's consciousness,

549
00:20:43,522 --> 00:20:44,656
Like with possession,

550
00:20:44,723 --> 00:20:46,190
But it does take lots of energy;

551
00:20:46,258 --> 00:20:48,059
The kind of energy you
need major motion to get--

552
00:20:48,126 --> 00:20:50,027
Hate, anger, love.

553
00:20:50,095 --> 00:20:51,829
Or guilt.

554
00:20:51,896 --> 00:20:53,830
Well, that depends. How much guilt?

555
00:20:53,898 --> 00:20:56,500
Well, in my vision, it was from
the point of view of the slasher.

556
00:20:56,568 --> 00:20:59,402
If I had slashed someone,
I'd feel pretty guilty.

557
00:20:59,470 --> 00:21:00,834
Then again, I'm not a slasher.

558
00:21:00,902 --> 00:21:02,234
Maybe the ghost wasn't, either.

559
00:21:02,302 --> 00:21:04,133
Which begs the question--

560
00:21:04,201 --> 00:21:06,133
Why did he say, "he needs me."

561
00:21:06,200 --> 00:21:08,701
Why would he need his son
to see him slashing someone?

562
00:21:08,769 --> 00:21:10,636
And who was he slashing? I don't know.

563
00:21:10,704 --> 00:21:12,037
It wasn't robert's girlfriend.
I don't think it was

564
00:21:12,105 --> 00:21:13,372
The ghost I saw outside the morgue.

565
00:21:13,440 --> 00:21:14,506
Why?

566
00:21:14,574 --> 00:21:15,740
'cause she wasn't cut or bloody.

567
00:21:15,808 --> 00:21:17,108
And you know what,
it was something else she said.

568
00:21:17,175 --> 00:21:19,143
She said, "he didn't mean to hurt her,"

569
00:21:19,210 --> 00:21:21,144
Not, "he didn't mean to hurt me."

570
00:21:21,212 --> 00:21:22,912
Then who's the victim? Yeah.

571
00:21:22,980 --> 00:21:24,947
Who's the woman outside the morgue?

572
00:21:25,015 --> 00:21:26,916
Why are so many of them crazy?

573
00:21:28,551 --> 00:21:30,453
No, I don't mind you asking at all.

574
00:21:30,520 --> 00:21:32,788
Frankly, I wish the hospital
had sent someone sooner.

575
00:21:32,855 --> 00:21:34,823
I know they're busy, but, you know.

576
00:21:34,891 --> 00:21:38,426
God forbid you have an issue that doesn't
fit into one of their neat little boxes.

577
00:21:38,494 --> 00:21:40,394
Like robert?

578
00:21:40,462 --> 00:21:42,062
Yeah.

579
00:21:42,130 --> 00:21:43,764
Here.

580
00:21:43,832 --> 00:21:45,399
Have a seat.

581
00:21:45,467 --> 00:21:48,402
Although, to be honest,

582
00:21:48,469 --> 00:21:51,270
I'm probably more mad at myself.

583
00:21:51,338 --> 00:21:53,004
For what? Well, I never asked

584
00:21:53,072 --> 00:21:56,105
The tough questions until my son started...

585
00:21:56,173 --> 00:21:59,908
Till things went so wrong with him.

586
00:21:59,976 --> 00:22:02,310
Do you mind describing what happened to him?

587
00:22:02,378 --> 00:22:04,578
Well, first it was simple insomnia.

588
00:22:04,646 --> 00:22:06,647
It started a few months ago.

589
00:22:06,714 --> 00:22:07,847
He couldn't sleep.

590
00:22:07,915 --> 00:22:09,348
Nothing would help.

591
00:22:09,416 --> 00:22:12,218
You know, exercise, pills, warm milk.

592
00:22:12,285 --> 00:22:13,452
Nothing.

593
00:22:13,520 --> 00:22:15,153
And then the nightmares started.

594
00:22:15,221 --> 00:22:16,821
I heard it in his voice.

595
00:22:16,889 --> 00:22:18,423
We'd talk all the time.

596
00:22:18,490 --> 00:22:20,391
He was different.

597
00:22:20,459 --> 00:22:21,592
And it affected his work.

598
00:22:21,660 --> 00:22:22,826
Pretty soon, he lost his job.

599
00:22:22,894 --> 00:22:25,995
He started to wander off,
disappearing from home.

600
00:22:26,063 --> 00:22:28,164
Like he did when he
showed up at the hospital.

601
00:22:28,232 --> 00:22:29,666
Helen, his girlfriend, she left her own job

602
00:22:29,733 --> 00:22:31,833
To try and help, but it was no use.

603
00:22:31,901 --> 00:22:33,602
The longer he went without sleep,

604
00:22:33,669 --> 00:22:34,936
The worse it got.

605
00:22:35,004 --> 00:22:37,004
You said you didn't ask the tough questions.

606
00:22:37,072 --> 00:22:39,706
What questions were those?

607
00:22:39,773 --> 00:22:41,307
I don't know if you have your own kids,

608
00:22:41,375 --> 00:22:43,074
Biologically, I mean.

609
00:22:43,142 --> 00:22:44,342
None that I know of.

610
00:22:44,410 --> 00:22:46,010
Anyway, I have to imagine

611
00:22:46,077 --> 00:22:47,611
It's different when you have your own.

612
00:22:47,679 --> 00:22:50,781
You never worry someone will
come along and lay claim to him.

613
00:22:50,849 --> 00:22:52,349
Was the adoption problematic?

614
00:22:52,417 --> 00:22:54,918
No, I don't mean, you know, literal claim.

615
00:22:54,986 --> 00:22:57,720
I mean, what if your child

616
00:22:57,788 --> 00:23:00,323
Decides he wants to connect
with his own people?

617
00:23:00,391 --> 00:23:01,924
And, you know, what if he discovers

618
00:23:01,992 --> 00:23:03,659
He has more in common
with them than with you?

619
00:23:03,727 --> 00:23:05,461
You were afraid of losing him.

620
00:23:05,529 --> 00:23:07,262
So when we adopted,

621
00:23:07,330 --> 00:23:09,431
They asked if we wanted to know

622
00:23:09,498 --> 00:23:11,265
Robert's family's circumstances.

623
00:23:11,333 --> 00:23:13,368
And I said, no, no, I didn't want to know.

624
00:23:13,436 --> 00:23:15,337
That all changed when he got sick.

625
00:23:15,404 --> 00:23:16,638
Of course, and I had to know.

626
00:23:16,705 --> 00:23:17,705
I wish I'd known sooner.

627
00:23:17,772 --> 00:23:19,206
Known what?

628
00:23:19,273 --> 00:23:20,806
Robert's parents didn't
choose to give him up.

629
00:23:20,874 --> 00:23:23,142
It wasn't up to them.

630
00:23:23,210 --> 00:23:25,711
He was a ward of the state.

631
00:23:25,778 --> 00:23:29,748
Was this, by any chance, because
robert's father had killed his mother?

632
00:23:29,815 --> 00:23:31,550
How did you know that?

633
00:23:31,618 --> 00:23:33,285
It's hard to explain, but I promise I will.

634
00:23:33,352 --> 00:23:35,753
Do you have any paperwork I can see?

635
00:23:38,056 --> 00:23:39,858
I understand that there are privacy issues,

636
00:23:39,926 --> 00:23:42,127
But I was hoping you'd still
want to help the family.

637
00:23:42,195 --> 00:23:44,929
You're forgetting that I'm retired now.

638
00:23:44,997 --> 00:23:47,064
Especially considering
the gaps in your report.

639
00:23:47,132 --> 00:23:48,465
What gaps?

640
00:23:48,533 --> 00:23:49,933
Robert's adopted father is how I found you.

641
00:23:50,001 --> 00:23:50,967
You were the social worker on the case.

642
00:23:51,035 --> 00:23:52,635
Yeah.

643
00:23:52,703 --> 00:23:55,704
Well, you left his birth
father's cause of death blank.

644
00:23:55,772 --> 00:23:57,939
But then you said it was
listed in appendix d,

645
00:23:58,007 --> 00:23:59,341
But there is no appendix d.

646
00:23:59,409 --> 00:24:01,143
So maybe it fell out of the file.

647
00:24:01,211 --> 00:24:03,979
That's when I realized that the
pages prove that nothing's missing.

648
00:24:04,047 --> 00:24:05,846
See, appendix c is on page 13

649
00:24:05,914 --> 00:24:07,348
And appendix e is on page 14,

650
00:24:07,416 --> 00:24:10,317
Meaning that there was never an appendix d.

651
00:24:10,385 --> 00:24:11,618
Was there?

652
00:24:12,753 --> 00:24:14,887
What do you want?

653
00:24:14,955 --> 00:24:18,090
I want to know what's
missing from the report.

654
00:24:18,158 --> 00:24:19,458
What do you know so far?

655
00:24:19,525 --> 00:24:21,059
His birth mother, marlene,

656
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:22,893
She died of uncontrolled bleeding

657
00:24:22,961 --> 00:24:24,728
Due to cuts on her forearms. And his father,

658
00:24:24,795 --> 00:24:27,230
Vernon, he was found on
the floor of a motel room

659
00:24:27,297 --> 00:24:28,764
Babbling incoherently.

660
00:24:28,831 --> 00:24:31,366
Yes, he blamed himself

661
00:24:31,433 --> 00:24:34,234
One minute, he blamed his wife the next.

662
00:24:34,302 --> 00:24:35,502
He also blamed demons.

663
00:24:36,971 --> 00:24:40,606
Yeah, there was talk about demons.

664
00:24:40,674 --> 00:24:43,408
And then he died in a psychiatric
ward not much after that.

665
00:24:43,476 --> 00:24:45,343
Ok, you say you worked with the hospital.

666
00:24:45,411 --> 00:24:47,479
Is robert sick? Yes.

667
00:24:47,547 --> 00:24:48,613
Why?

668
00:24:48,681 --> 00:24:50,915
Is he suffering from insomnia,
by any chance?

669
00:24:52,384 --> 00:24:55,585
What else is missing from that report?

670
00:24:55,653 --> 00:24:58,322
No one would have adopted that boy

671
00:24:58,389 --> 00:25:00,125
If they knew the truth.

672
00:25:00,193 --> 00:25:01,728
The truth?

673
00:25:01,797 --> 00:25:03,299
That his father killed his mother.

674
00:25:03,366 --> 00:25:04,668
That he was insane.

675
00:25:04,736 --> 00:25:07,005
Because psychosis is genetic.

676
00:25:07,073 --> 00:25:09,274
Because at the time,
it seemed like the worst thing

677
00:25:09,341 --> 00:25:11,375
You could pass on to a child.

678
00:25:11,443 --> 00:25:13,577
At the time? Was there something else?

679
00:25:13,645 --> 00:25:16,614
The doctors didn't even know
that the disease existed,

680
00:25:16,682 --> 00:25:19,584
Not until there was another death
in the family like vernon's.

681
00:25:19,652 --> 00:25:22,120
A woman, robert's sister.

682
00:25:22,187 --> 00:25:23,721
Extremely rare.

683
00:25:23,789 --> 00:25:26,024
It's called fatal familial insomnia.

684
00:25:26,092 --> 00:25:27,392
And if a parent has it,

685
00:25:27,460 --> 00:25:29,561
You have a 50% chance of inheriting it.

686
00:25:29,629 --> 00:25:31,396
So how is it treated?

687
00:25:31,464 --> 00:25:33,598
It's not. There's no cure.

688
00:25:33,666 --> 00:25:36,033
The body can't live without rest.

689
00:25:36,101 --> 00:25:38,435
Yeah, for a few weeks,

690
00:25:38,503 --> 00:25:39,637
Months at the most.

691
00:25:39,704 --> 00:25:41,338
After that, psychosis sets in.

692
00:25:41,406 --> 00:25:43,474
Organ failure.

693
00:25:43,541 --> 00:25:45,141
And death.

694
00:25:47,510 --> 00:25:50,479
It says in the obit lane dokes died

695
00:25:50,547 --> 00:25:51,880
Of an undisclosed illness.

696
00:25:56,654 --> 00:25:58,053
Yep.

697
00:25:58,121 --> 00:25:59,355
That's robert's sister.

698
00:25:59,422 --> 00:26:00,989
It's the ghost I saw outside the morgue.

699
00:26:01,057 --> 00:26:02,424
She was 24.

700
00:26:02,492 --> 00:26:04,559
Her father died in his early thirties.

701
00:26:04,627 --> 00:26:06,294
Kids got split up after that.

702
00:26:06,361 --> 00:26:09,196
She went into foster care
and robert got luckier.

703
00:26:09,264 --> 00:26:11,332
Yeah, if you call that luck.

704
00:26:11,399 --> 00:26:12,833
Coming down with a fatal
disease that I wouldn't wish

705
00:26:12,900 --> 00:26:14,568
On my worst ex-girlfriend.

706
00:26:14,635 --> 00:26:15,935
When she said he didn't mean to hurt her,

707
00:26:16,003 --> 00:26:17,570
She was talking about the father.

708
00:26:17,638 --> 00:26:19,472
When she said he wasn't dangerous...

709
00:26:19,540 --> 00:26:20,640
She meant her brother.

710
00:26:20,707 --> 00:26:22,708
Yeah. Obviously, she's still very confused.

711
00:26:22,776 --> 00:26:25,211
That's what happens when
most of what you remember

712
00:26:25,278 --> 00:26:27,679
From your final days is hallucinatory.

713
00:26:27,746 --> 00:26:28,913
Poor dead looney tune.

714
00:26:28,981 --> 00:26:30,147
Yeah, I have to tell robert.

715
00:26:30,215 --> 00:26:32,216
Tell him what? "hey, good news,

716
00:26:32,283 --> 00:26:33,417
"you probably didn't kill anyone.

717
00:26:33,484 --> 00:26:35,151
"bad news is visions that
made you think you did,

718
00:26:35,219 --> 00:26:37,019
"are little home movies of dad killing mom.

719
00:26:37,087 --> 00:26:38,921
"oh, and by the way,
he and your sister went bonko

720
00:26:38,989 --> 00:26:41,590
And died of a fatal disease
that you inherited."

721
00:26:44,894 --> 00:26:46,928
I gotta call you back.

722
00:27:28,098 --> 00:27:31,434
Wake up quick, before it's too late.

723
00:28:05,394 --> 00:28:06,594
Hey, hey, hey, whoa.

724
00:28:06,662 --> 00:28:08,296
Are you ok?

725
00:28:11,299 --> 00:28:13,300
Depends on which melinda you're asking.

726
00:28:13,368 --> 00:28:14,601
Sorry?

727
00:28:14,669 --> 00:28:16,669
I'll explain later. What's going on?

728
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:17,937
Robert's gone.

729
00:28:18,005 --> 00:28:19,639
Gone-gone?

730
00:28:19,706 --> 00:28:20,739
Yeah, they searched the hospital.
He's nowhere.

731
00:28:20,807 --> 00:28:22,908
He's disappeared.

732
00:28:24,744 --> 00:28:26,711
His name is robert wharton.

733
00:28:26,779 --> 00:28:28,746
I'm his girlfriend, can't you find him?

734
00:28:33,951 --> 00:28:34,851
Thanks.

735
00:28:35,169 --> 00:28:36,669
I just needed some air.

736
00:28:36,737 --> 00:28:38,571
We're sorry to add to your worries.

737
00:28:38,639 --> 00:28:41,373
There's no cure? You're sure?

738
00:28:41,441 --> 00:28:43,109
There's no cure?

739
00:28:43,176 --> 00:28:45,073
That's what we've been told.

740
00:28:45,140 --> 00:28:47,274
And you think his father is haunting him?

741
00:28:47,342 --> 00:28:48,509
Why?

742
00:28:48,577 --> 00:28:50,277
Maybe to warn him. We're not sure.

743
00:28:51,979 --> 00:28:55,847
What's awful is this is the
first thing I've heard in weeks

744
00:28:55,915 --> 00:28:57,549
That actually makes sense.

745
00:28:57,616 --> 00:29:00,417
When you get used to your
boyfriend's boss calling,

746
00:29:00,485 --> 00:29:02,552
Asking if he's drinking for breakfast.

747
00:29:02,620 --> 00:29:04,520
Do you mind telling us what happened

748
00:29:04,588 --> 00:29:06,155
Before he disappeared?

749
00:29:06,223 --> 00:29:09,191
You mean after he lost his job?

750
00:29:09,258 --> 00:29:13,094
He started calling all times,

751
00:29:13,161 --> 00:29:14,528
Day and night,

752
00:29:14,596 --> 00:29:17,164
Asking strange, bizarre questions.

753
00:29:17,232 --> 00:29:19,534
Sometimes he'd accuse me of things.

754
00:29:19,602 --> 00:29:20,968
He sounded paranoid?

755
00:29:21,036 --> 00:29:24,372
At first I thought it was
a bad case of cold feet.

756
00:29:24,440 --> 00:29:26,140
Cold feet?

757
00:29:26,208 --> 00:29:29,343
We'd just recently talked
about getting married,

758
00:29:29,411 --> 00:29:32,079
Maybe even having kids.

759
00:29:33,682 --> 00:29:35,316
Did he ever tell you about
dreams he may have had?

760
00:29:35,384 --> 00:29:37,685
Hallucinations?

761
00:29:37,753 --> 00:29:39,553
Yes.

762
00:29:39,621 --> 00:29:40,955
A lot.

763
00:29:41,022 --> 00:29:42,723
The second he would close his eyes,

764
00:29:42,791 --> 00:29:44,958
Or sometimes even when
his eyes were still open,

765
00:29:45,026 --> 00:29:47,160
He would see these creatures.

766
00:29:47,228 --> 00:29:49,462
Uh, I don't remember what he called them.

767
00:29:49,530 --> 00:29:51,731
Demons?

768
00:29:51,799 --> 00:29:54,767
That's right. Demons.

769
00:29:54,834 --> 00:29:56,601
Do you know what that means?

770
00:29:56,669 --> 00:29:59,469
Vernon, his birth father,
said that he saw demons, too.

771
00:29:59,536 --> 00:30:01,703
I thought they were all just delusions.

772
00:30:01,771 --> 00:30:04,439
Are you telling me that they weren't?

773
00:30:04,506 --> 00:30:06,039
Hey. Hey.

774
00:30:06,107 --> 00:30:07,173
Did you find anything?

775
00:30:07,241 --> 00:30:09,208
Yeah, robert's brain scans just came back,

776
00:30:09,276 --> 00:30:12,043
And, um, they don't show any physical damage

777
00:30:12,111 --> 00:30:14,378
Or abnormalities that would
explain the symptoms.

778
00:30:15,780 --> 00:30:20,317
So he has it. It's in his blood.

779
00:30:20,384 --> 00:30:23,019
How else would you explain the insomnia?

780
00:30:24,588 --> 00:30:25,621
Look...

781
00:30:25,689 --> 00:30:27,222
How long does he have?

782
00:30:27,290 --> 00:30:28,590
Wait a minute, wait a minute, helen.

783
00:30:28,658 --> 00:30:31,059
This doesn't mean that he has ffi.

784
00:30:31,126 --> 00:30:32,693
We don't know that yet.

785
00:30:32,761 --> 00:30:34,128
There are tests that can
better determine that.

786
00:30:34,196 --> 00:30:36,730
But even if he has the disease,

787
00:30:36,798 --> 00:30:38,464
There are remedies for
these kinds of things.

788
00:30:38,532 --> 00:30:40,165
I mean, treatments.

789
00:30:40,233 --> 00:30:41,900
Obscure stuff that no one knows about

790
00:30:41,967 --> 00:30:43,934
